  <title>Activity over Sections 1.1-1.2</title>

  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the first four terms of each of the following sequences given by these explicit formulas:
        </p>
      </introduction>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          <m>a_{n} = 3^{n-1}</m> for <m>n \geq 1</m>
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          <m>a_{n} = n^{2} + (-1)^{n}</m> for <m>n \geq 0</m>
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Find the first four terms of each of the following sequences given by these recurrence relations:
        </p>
      </introduction>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          <m>a_{1} = 5</m>, <m>a_{n} = a_{n-1}+ 10</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          <m>a_{1} = -4</m>, <m>a_{n} = a_{n-1}+ n</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          <m>a_{0} = 2</m>, <m>a_{1} = 4</m>, <m>a_{n} = a_{n-2}+ a_{n-1}</m> for <m>n \geq 2</m>
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>


  <page>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Let <m>a_{n} = (-4)^{n}</m> for <m>n \geq 0</m>.
        </p>
      </introduction>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          Find <m>a_{0}, a_{1}, a_{2},</m> and <m>a_{3}</m>.
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          Show that <m>a_{2} = -3a_{1} +4a_{0}</m> and <m>a_{3} = -3a_{2} +4a_{1}</m>
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1.5in">
        <p>
          Show that <m>a_{n} = -3a_{n-1}+4a_{n-2}</m> for all integers <m>n</m> with <m>n \geq 2</m>.
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          An employee joined a company in 2022 with a starting salary of $50,000.
          Every year this employee receives a raise of $500 plus 1%of the salary of the previous year.
        </p>
      </introduction>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          Set up a recurrence relation for the salary of this employee <m>n</m> years after 2022.
        </p>
      </task>
    
      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          What will the salary of this employee be in 2027?
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
  <page>
    <exercise >
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>n</m> is any positive integer.
          Let <m>a_{n}</m> denote the number of different ways we can express <m>n</m> as the sum of 1s and 2s.
          For example, <m>a_{3} = 3</m> since the number 3 can be expressed as the sum of 1s and 2s in 3 different ways:
          <me>
            3 = 1 + 1 + 1 = 1 + 2 = 2 + 1
          </me>
        </p>
      </introduction>


      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <p>
          What is <m>a_{1}</m>?
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <p>
          What is <m>a_{2}</m>?
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <p>
          What is <m>a_{4}</m>?
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="0.5in">
        <p>
          What is <m>a_{5}</m>?
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="1in">
        <p>
          What is your conjecture for what <m>a_{n}</m> is for any <m>n \geq 1</m>?
        </p>
      </task>


      <task workspace="2in">
        <p>
          Use your conjecture to make a prediction for <m>a_{7}</m> and then actually compute <m>a_{7}</m> by finding all the ways to write 7 as the sum of 1s and 2s.
        </p>
      </task>
    </exercise>
  </page>
